Anyway, back to this week's email...

In 1994, Pixar released one of my favourite movies and the first
full-length animated film, Toy Story.

It was groundbreaking â€” the first entirely computer-animated
movie ever made â€” and it set the stage for a legacy of
storytelling magic.

â€‹
But hereâ€™s the thing about Pixar: their success isnâ€™t just about
brilliant ideas or creative geniuses. Itâ€™s about their process.

And at the heart of this process is something they call the
Braintrust.

The Braintrust is a feedback system that Pixar uses for every
single film, where the studioâ€™s most experienced storytellers
meet to review rough drafts of each project.

These sessions are known for their brutal honesty. Thereâ€™s no
sugarcoating. No egos. Just raw constructive criticism designed
to identify problems and push each project forward.

Take Toy Story 2, for example. Early drafts of the film were
apparently pretty terrible.

The story was disjointed, the characters felt one-dimensional,
and the pacing didnâ€™t work. In a traditional system, this might
have led to a panicked scramble or shelving the project entirely.

But, at Pixar, the Braintrust helped the team break the film
down, problem by problem. Over months of reflection, reworking,
and iteration, Toy Story 2 transformed into the masterpiece that
we now all know and love.

And, so, this is the real secret to their magic. Their ideas are
good, sure. But, itâ€™s the systems they have in place that turn
those ideas into something extraordinary.

The Power of Reflection
-----------------------

The Braintrustâ€™s focus on deliberate reflection isnâ€™t just unique
to Pixar, of course. Itâ€™s something we should also be doing in
our own lives.

Psychologist Anders Ericsson, in his research on deliberate
practice, found that the best performers in any field donâ€™t just
practice more â€” they practice smarter. They constantly reflect on
their performance, identify weaknesses, and tweak their approach.

Itâ€™s the same reason journaling is such a powerful tool.

Studies published in The European Journal of Social Psychology
show that writing about our experiences â€” even for just a few
minutes a day â€” helps us process challenges, clarify our goals,
and improve decision-making.

Pixarâ€™s Braintrust, in many ways, functions like a company-wide
journal. Itâ€™s a built-in system for reflection and improvement,
ensuring that no project, no matter how ambitious, veers too far
off track.

Iteration Over Perfection
-------------------------

Pixarâ€™s story also reminds me of an idea James Clear explores in
Atomic Habits: the idea that success is built on small,
consistent improvements (rather than one-off bursts of effort).

In fact, researchers call this the aggregation of marginal gains.
Coined by Sir Dave Brailsford during his tenure with British
Cycling, itâ€™s the idea that improving by just 1% in multiple
areas compounds into extraordinary results.

Pixar embodies this principle. Their films donâ€™t emerge fully
formed, of course. Theyâ€™re the result of hundreds of small
iterations â€” each Braintrust meeting, each edit, each tweak â€”
compounding over time into something incredible.

Ed Catmull, one of the studioâ€™s co-founders, writes in
Creativity, Inc. that â€œearly on, all of our movies suck.â€ But
they donâ€™t aim for perfection from the start. Instead, they
embrace the process of iteration, knowing that greatness comes
from the willingness to improve, step by step.

So, the takeaway here is that whether youâ€™re working on a
creative project, building a habit, or chasing a big goal, the
magic doesnâ€™t happen all at once. Itâ€™s not about waiting for
inspiration to strike or getting it perfect on the first try.

The magic is in the process: reflecting, refining, and showing up
consistently. Thatâ€™s how ideas turn into achievements â€” and how
something good becomes something great.

Speak soon,

Ali xx

column7: âœï¸ 110,000 People Registered for This Workshop: Here's What We Learned
column9:
Hey friends,

Big thank you to everyone who attended Spark 2025 over the
weekend, the 2-day free online workshop that my team and I
hosted. We had 110,000 people registered for it, and around
18-20k concurrent attendees for each of the sessions. Pretty
insane number - for context, Wembley Stadium in London holds
12,000 people, so we had like 1.5 stadiums worth of people
joining in on Zoom from all around the world, all doing various
reflection and goal-setting exercises together.

Solid vibes throughout - and if youâ€™re interested, you can see
some of the â€œtestimonialsâ€ of sorts that people left for the
event here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehpz7qmehxh620lm77i5/owhkhwurel82vktq/aHR0cHM6Ly90ZXN0aW1vbmlhbC50by9hbGktZXZlbnRzL2FsbA==
). The team and I have been reading through these over the past
couple of days with big smiles on our faces.

In this email, I wanted to share some of the journaling prompts
we went through (along with some of the results of the
interactive quizzes we did), so that if you didnâ€™t get a chance
to attend, you can maybe have a stab at doing some of these
yourself. And if you did attend, (a) hopefully you got value from
the session, and (b) you might like to see this list as a
reminder + maybe some more things come to mind the second time
you think about them.

âœï¸ 2024 Reflections
-------------------

We started Day #1 off with a visualisation exercise to
re-experience the year, and feel into the most salient moments of
2024. There was a few minutes of this, with some vibey music.
Then, we spent 3 minutes on the following prompts.

* ðŸ† Major Milestones - What were the most significant events or
achievements in 2024 for you? How did these impact your life?
* ðŸ™ Gratitude - What are you most grateful for in 2024? Think
about people, experiences, or opportunities that enriched your
life.
* ðŸ’ª Challenges - What were the biggest challenges or obstacles
you faced in 2024? How did you overcome them, and what did you
learn from these experiences?
* ðŸŽ“ Professional Growth - How did you progress in your career /
work in 2024? What were the key learnings and how have they
shaped your future aspirations?
* ðŸŒ± Personal Growth - In what ways have you grown or changed as a
person over the past year? Consider changes in your beliefs,
attitudes, and behaviours.
* âŒ Unfulfilled Aspirations - Were there goals or aspirations you
had for 2024 that you didnâ€™t achieve? Reflect on why they were
not met and how you feel about it.
* ðŸ‘¥ Relationships and Connections - Reflect on your relationships
in 2024. How have they evolved? Were there new relationships that
had a significant impact on you?
* ðŸš€ Looking Forward - Based on your experiences in 2024, what
would you like to do differently in 2025? * What would you like
to continue doing?
* What would you like to start doing?
* What would you like to stop doing?

When we did an interactive word-cloud poll asking: â€Whatâ€™s 1
small action youâ€™ll commit to taking TODAY to make a start
towards your dream 2025?â€, the most common answers were:
planning, journaling, reading, meditation, going for a walk,
waking up early, sleeping early, goal-setting, exercising.

â€‹

ðŸª¦ Write your Own Eulogy
-----------------------

We then moved into a morbid-at-first-glance-but-really-useful
exercise involving visualising your own funeral (in a world where
you live to be 100 years old in great physical and mental
health), and imagining what youâ€™d like different people to say at
your funeral.

* Today, we gather to honour the life and legacy of [name]
* [Name] was aâ€¦
* In his personal life, heâ€¦
* Those closest to him remember him asâ€¦
* In his professional life, heâ€¦
* His work will be remembered for its contribution toâ€¦
* He was an inspiration to others becauseâ€¦
* The story of his life teaches us thatâ€¦
* Heâ€™ll always be remembered as someone who lived withâ€¦
* Finally, if [name] were here with us today, heâ€™d remind us
thatâ€¦

When we did a word cloud interactive poll thingy to ask how
people found that experience, the top responses were: inspiring,
emotional, motivating, enlightening, clarifying, sad,
thought-provoking and insightful.

â€‹
And when asked: â€œBased on your eulogy, what would you like to
START doing in 2025?â€, by far the most common answer was â€œtaking
actionâ€. Other common answers were: living, learning, connecting,
planning, writing, travel.

â€‹

âœ¨ Dopamine Hacking
------------------

We then had a wonderful workshop from neuroscientist TJ Power
themed around taking control of our dopamine. TJâ€™s book The Dose
Effect (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehpz7qmehxh620lm77i5/p8hehquze57n0dur/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL2hFRTk=
) is out next week - Iâ€™ve preordered and canâ€™t wait to read it ðŸ˜Š
The session had a lot of interactive stuff in it around
actionable, tactical ways to break our addiction to fast-and-easy
dopamine. This video â€œHow to Reset your Dopamine and Change your
Life (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehpz7qmehxh620lm77i5/kkhmh2ulp29kq9hk/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS9sNkJvU09SWENVZz9zaT1CeXMxWVJwcVJQMHdMZEg3
)â€ is one I made in collaboration with TJ a few months ago, if
youâ€™d like to get a sense of what we covered in the workshop.

ðŸ¤‘ The 5 Types of Wealth
-----------------------

We ended Day #1 with a fantastic workshop by entrepreneur and
investor Sahil Bloom, about the 5 Types of Wealth - physical
wealth, social wealth, time wealth, mental wealth and financial
wealth.

Spark participants all took the Wealth Score Quiz (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehpz7qmehxh620lm77i5/25h2h9u2x0okz2f8/aHR0cHM6Ly93ZWFsdGhzY29yZXF1aXouY29tLw==
) (you can take it here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehpz7qmehxh620lm77i5/25h2h9u2x0okz2f8/aHR0cHM6Ly93ZWFsdGhzY29yZXF1aXouY29tLw==
) if youâ€™d like) - this image shows our collective results for
each type of wealth. Broadly, Spark attendees had pretty good
scores for Mental Wealth and Social Wealth, but Financial Wealth
was a little sparser than the others.

â€‹
Sahilâ€™s book of the same name The 5 Types of Wealth (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehpz7qmehxh620lm77i5/g3hnhwu32oz456t3/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL2tqaUlx
) is also coming out in February - Iâ€™ve preordered this one too ðŸ˜‰

We wrapped up Day #1 by revisiting our action points and
commitments to ourselves, with some homework over the next 18
hours in preparation for Day #2.

Hopefully you got some value out of seeing what went down in the
workshops - if youâ€™d like a summary of what we did in Day #2 as
well, please let me know by replying to this email and if thereâ€™s
a good amount of interest, Iâ€™ll do a write-up of Day #2 too.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

B


p ChatGPT Gets "Study Mode" to Stop Students From Cheating

 * OpenAI launched Study Mode that refuses to give homework answers until students actually engage with the material. It's like
   having a tutor that won't let you copy.

 * Why it matters: AI companies are trying to rebrand from "homework destroyer" to "educational tool" before teachers ban them
   entirely.

B


p0 Nvidia Challenger Groq Raises $600M, Valued at $6B

 * AI chip startup Groq is raising $600 million at a $6 billion valuation, doubling its worth in one year. Investors are throwing
   money at anything that isn't Nvidia.

 * Why it matters: The AI hardware war is getting expensive, and VCs are betting billions that someone, somewhere can build chips
   faster than Jensen's leather jacket empire.

B


p- iPhone Maker Foxconn Pivots to Building AI Data Centers

 * Foxconn is partnering with TECO to build AI data centers because apparently assembling iPhones isn't profitable enough anymore.

 * Why it matters: The entire tech supply chain is retooling for AI. The companies that built your phone are now building the
   infrastructure to replace your brain.

B


p Apple Feels the Heat from Tariffs and Slow AI Rollout

 * Apple's facing pressure from potential tariffs and competition in China, plus everyone's noticing they're hilariously behind in
   AI. Siri's big upgrade got delayed until next year.

 * Why it matters: Even the world's most valuable company isn't immune to AI FOMO. Being late to the AI party is like showing up
   to the internet in 2010 b technically possible, but embarrassing.

B


p' Spotify Wants Its AI to Actually Understand Your Terrible Music Taste

 * Spotify is using data from AI DJ requests to build a more conversational AI that can "reason" about your listening habits
   instead of just guessing.

 * Why it matters: Soon your music app will judge your playlist choices with the sophistication of a human friend, but without the
   ability to stage an intervention.

B


p$ AI Video Tools Pivot from Hollywood to Robots

 * Luma and Runway are talking to robotics companies about using their video AI to help machines understand the 3D world. Because
   apparently making TikToks wasn't ambitious enough.

 * Why it matters: The same tech creating viral videos could become the visual cortex for the robots that will eventually replace
   us. Full circle.

B


p$ Voice Actors Fight AI Dubbing, Viewers Fight Bad AI Dubbing

 * European voice actors want new regulations to protect their jobs from AI dubbing. Meanwhile, Netflix pulled some AI-dubbed
   shows after viewers complained they sounded like robots.

 * Why it matters: AI is simultaneously threatening creative jobs and proving it's not ready to replace them. The future is
   awkward.

B


p Berkeley Dropouts Raise $28M for AI Marketing Startup

 * Two 19-year-old UC Berkeley dropouts raised $28 million for Conversion, an AI marketing automation startup. They're disrupting
   legacy tools by building AI-first instead of bolting it on later.

 * Why it matters: Classic Silicon Valley story for the AI age b drop out, build AI-native product, get rich, make everyone else
   feel old.

(of course I gave yâ€™all a keyâ€¦ I mean Iâ€™m a data expertðŸ˜‰)
Here are all of my past roles:
Server: $5/hour 
Graduate Assistant: $17/hour + tuition waved
Data Analyst Intern: $17/hour ðŸš€
Data Analyst: $71,500 + $19K bonuses
Senior Data Analyst: $73K
Data Analytics Manager: $95K ðŸª©
Senior Risk Analyst: $130 + $9K bonus ðŸª©ðŸš€
Senior Data Analyst: $153K ðŸª©ðŸš€
Job Hopping and Cashing in ðŸ¤‘
For my first Data Analytics role, I didnâ€™t negotiate my salary much because I didnâ€™t think I was worth it. (donâ€™t follow in my footsteps here, PLEASE negotiate even if itâ€™s your first role! Companies expect you to, and if you donâ€™t youâ€™re leaving money on the table!!)
Then I was later promoted in title a year later but I didnâ€™t receive a salary increase. I tried and they said no. They didnâ€™t have a lot of budget, and I didnâ€™t come as prepared as I shouldâ€™ve beenâ€¦ UNTILâ€¦
When I was promoted again to Data Analytics Manager, I advocated for a salary adjustment (+29%) since I was managing people, planning projects, and growing in leadership and responsibility within the company. I truly deserved it. I wrote a 1-pager with all of my accomplishments over the past year, the additional duties I was performing, and the average market salary from multiple sources. I provided all the evidence and data to support a salary increase. I made it easy to say yes. 
Then, I moved to a different company as a Senior Risk Analyst because I knew itâ€™s what I had to do to continue to grow my skills. I had several competing offers for higher salaries which showed me my true worth and allowed me to negotiate a higher salary at my chosen company (+37%). I let the market decide my salary through multiple offers instead of guessing random numbers in interviews. I used my other offers as leverage to get more money!
In my most recent job switch 2.5+ years ago, I was seeking a new growth opportunity and increased my salary by 18%. I attribute my success in this switch to working really hard on my interviewing and communication skills. I focused on how to communicate my value through the STAR method, live coding, and statistics.
This puts me at a ~110% increase from $73K to $153K in only 11 monthsâ€¦ I got an internal raise by self-advocating for myself with a 1-pager and then job hopped twice. I had a busy year, OK ðŸ˜… Itâ€™s not ideal to job hop twice in 1 year, but my senior risk analyst job ended up being not what I wanted and a terrible fit, so I left in 4 months. But hey, I did get another salary increase!!
Here are my biggest salary takeaways:
ALWAYS negotiate your salary (Notice how my salary grew when I started negotiating!)
Be on top of the market valueâ€” know your worth and talk to others in your field.
Donâ€™t lowball yourselfâ€” let the market decide your value.
Practice interviewingâ€” show your value through communication and tech interviews. 
Be transparent with othersâ€” you never know who you might help!
This was inspired by a few conversations I've had recently with entry-level analysts who were bummed to get offers lower than expected. I shared my salary trajectory with them and reassured them that they could increase their salary quickly after getting some valuable experience. It really helped motivate them to see the upward potential in this field, and I think they felt better knowing that a 6 figure Data Analytics salary isnâ€™t realistic for your first role.
Being transparent can only help others.
What's your salary? ðŸ‘€

Hey Candace,

When I uploaded my first YouTube video back in 2017, I had no clue what I was doing.

I didnâ€™t have a grand master plan. My editing skills were non-existent, my lighting setup wasâ€¦ questionable, and I was balancing it all alongside my full-time job as a junior doctor.

But I had one thing going for me: I told myself Iâ€™d upload at least one video every week, no matter what.

The first few videos barely got any views â€” just a handful of friends and my mum watching them. But I stuck with it, because Iâ€™d read somewhere that the key to success wasnâ€™t about doing something extraordinary once. It was about showing up consistently and letting those small efforts compound over time.

Fast-forward a few years, and that simple commitment to consistency is what grew my channel to where it is today, with over 6 million subscribers and counting (https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VWMqCt2Gjrr8W6qh60m2mkSjMW6YVQGc5p53ZMN8DGmDn3pyd0W7lCdLW6lZ3lXW8mHPZ-8mykvPW4ym16z5c-Gf_VyLTT85l6wbZW13W52c2ZMgySW3J4SkH6G-CZ5N2Fqyl-ht95bN7v5M8mkL08PW8tj3_d6PJ8qMW4zHVQB2QK_1jW4HnlSC1h1MrwW1Rd7Y-94pnv4N5-WbkG7MmP1W513SZd8D69ffW8brDXz12js95W4XxP9z5n0KSCW5FhC1K6kh_8mVx0W0B7ljHG2W7YMpWQ9jkzlFW65HQQV8JRmR7V_lSf73jNWCQW143Rpn2c-M_vW4C3TyT4z7ZG1W72200z62Lt4YW2WM5gH5z2BGtf8FWFVT04 ) (as of today ðŸ˜œ).

The productivity principle here is simple but powerful: Consistency beats intensity.

Itâ€™s tempting to think that success comes from one big, breakthrough moment. But in reality, itâ€™s about the tiny, boring steps you take day after day. As James Clear puts it in Atomic Habits, â€œYou donâ€™t rise to the level of your goals. You fall to the level of your systems.â€

This idea of consistency ties into what psychologists call the compound effect.

Each small action â€” each upload, each edit, each thumbnail tweak â€” might not feel like much on its own. But over time, those small actions add up, multiplying into something much bigger.

Thereâ€™s even a concept in Japanese philosophy called kaizen, which means â€œcontinuous improvement.â€ Itâ€™s the idea of focusing on small, consistent progress rather than perfection. Thatâ€™s what helped Toyota revolutionise manufacturing, and itâ€™s the same mindset that can revolutionise your productivity, too.
